  <h2>Why Monsoon Is the Riskiest Period</h2>
  <p>
    The monsoon brings relief from summer heat but introduces serious challenges for shrimp farmers across Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Gujarat, Odisha, and West Bengal. Heavy rainfall causes rapid parameter shifts that can wipe out a crop in days:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>pH crashes:</strong> Freshwater influx dilutes alkalinity, causing sudden pH drops that stress shrimp and stop feeding</li>
    <li><strong>DO drops:</strong> Cloud cover reduces photosynthesis while organic runoff increases oxygen demand, creating dangerous night-time lows</li>
    <li><strong>Ammonia spikes:</strong> Runoff carries fertilizer and organic matter into ponds, overwhelming the biological filter</li>
    <li><strong>Disease outbreaks:</strong> Stressed shrimp with weakened immunity become susceptible to Vibrio, WSSV, and other pathogens</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The farmers who survive monsoon with healthy stock are the ones who prepare before the first storm. Here is your practical monsoon management plan.
  </p>

  <h2>Pre-Monsoon Preparation</h2>
  <p>
    Start these preparations at least two weeks before the monsoon is forecast to arrive in your region:
  </p>

  <h3>Strengthen Pond Infrastructure</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Inspect and reinforce pond walls and dykes — look for cracks, burrows, and erosion points</li>
    <li>Clean and deepen drainage canals to handle excess water flow</li>
    <li>Install overflow pipes or spillways at the correct water level</li>
    <li>Check inlet screens to prevent wild fish and debris from entering</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Check Aeration Systems</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Service all aerators — replace worn paddles, clean air stones, test backup generators</li>
    <li>Ensure you have enough aeration capacity for peak biomass plus monsoon margin</li>
    <li>Keep spare aerator parts and a fuel reserve for generators on hand</li>
  </ul>

